<h6 class="kicker">Current Events</h6>
<p class="summary">Teaching ideas based on New York Times content.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="/category/current-events/">See all in Current Events Â»</a></li>
<li><a title="See all Lesson Plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/">See all lesson plans Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong><em>Updated: March 3, 2014</em></strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Overview |</strong> Why is Ukraine experiencing so much political unrest? What role do Russia, Europe and the United States play in the turmoil? How did this conflict begin, and how will it end? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If you watched the <a href="//sochi2014.nytimes.com/">Winter Olympics</a> over the past two weeks, you saw that Russia pulled off world-class athletic competitions and dazzling opening and closing ceremonies in Sochi. But by the end of the second week, the escalating violence and instability in nearby Ukraine cast a shadow over the Games.  In this lesson, students will learn about the political and economic crisis consuming Ukraine, first by getting an overview of the basic facts and then by digging deeper in small research groups.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-142903"></span><br />
<strong>Materials |</strong> Computer with Internet connection and projector to display articles and video, computers with Internet connection for individual students or groups to use online resources, or copies of articles or documents as needed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly>
<div class="w190 right module">
<div class="entry">
<h5 class="kicker">RELATED RESOURCES</h5>
<h6>From The Learning Network</h6>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/14/behind-the-olympics-teaching-about-russia-in-the-putin-era/">Behind the Olympics: Teaching About Russia in the Putin Era</a></li>
<li><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/20/6-qs-about-the-news-blaze-and-bloodshed-in-kiev/">6 Qâs About the News | Blaze and Bloodshed in Kiev</a></li>
<li><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/12/09/6-qs-about-the-news-hundreds-of-thousands-protest-in-kiev/">6 Qâs About the News | Hundreds of Thousands Protest in Kiev</a></li>
<li><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/09/poetry-pairing-ozymandias/">Poetry Pairing | âOzymandiasâ</a></li>
</ul>
<h6>From NYTimes.com</h6>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/international/countriesandterritories/ukraine/index.html">Times Topics | Ukraine</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/cfr/international/20050301faessay_v84n2_karatnycky.html">Ukraine&#8217;s Orange Revolution</a></li>
</ul>
<h6>Around the Web</h6>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="//www.choices.edu/resources/twtn/twtn-ukraine.php">The Choices Program | Unrest in Ukraine</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26270866">BBC | Ukraine Crisis</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"></webonly></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Warm-Up |</strong> Begin by asking students: What do you know about Ukraine? Where is it? Why is it in the news lately? What events are taking place there? And why?  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As students share what they know and what they&#8217;ve heard, you may want to use this <a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/activities/KWL_NYTLN.pdf">K/W/L chart</a> (PDF) so students can organize their ideas. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then, watch the above video <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000002724416/the-ukraine-divide-explained.html">âThe Ukraine Divide, Explainedâ</a> and study the map of Ukraine embedded in<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/23/world/europe/with-presidents-departure-ukraine-looks-toward-a-murky-future.html"> this article</a>.  Ask students, how are divisions in Ukraine responsible for the current unrest? Students can add these notes to their K/W/L chart.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then ask students to generate questions they have about what&#8217;s going on in Ukraine.  They can share these questions with the class, and add them to their K/W/L chart as well.</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Related |</strong> In the article <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/23/world/europe/a-broken-promise-and-a-cold-war-fight.html">âHow It All Began: A Cold War Battle Heats Up,â</a> David M. Herszenhorn explains the core factors responsible for the revolution taking place in Ukraine and the events that led up to it.</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Three months of civic unrest in Ukraine spiraled out of control last week with dozens of people dead, the center of this elegant city turned into a burning war zone and the eventual flight from the capital Saturday by the president. Puzzled about the conflict and how it got so bad? Hereâs a primer.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Questions | </strong>Read the entire article with your class and answer the questions below.</p>
<ol>
<li>What are the three core factors that led to the chaos, according to the article?</li>
<li>Why does Russia feel threatened by Ukraine forming a closer partnership with Europe?</li>
<li>Why did many Ukrainians, especially in the Western part of the country, want Ukraine to sign political and economic agreements with the European Union?</li>
<li>Why did street protests erupt in November 2013?</li>
<li>What were some of the government missteps that helped further fuel the protests?</li>
<li>What additional questions do you have about what&#8217;s going on in Ukraine?</li>
</ol>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Activity |</strong> After watching the video and reading the article, students should have a basic understanding of what&#8217;s happening in Ukraine.  But to go deeper, the class can work in small groups to analyze a specific question about the crisis. We&#8217;ve organized articles, videos, interactives and slide shows in The New York Times based on six questions about Ukraine, though you may want to use the questions that your students generated earlier in this lesson to organize the research groups. When students have completed their research, they can either <a href="//www.jigsaw.org/overview.htm">jigsaw</a> what theyâve learned, or make presentations to the class &#8212; so all students can more fully understand the complex events taking place in Ukraine.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How did the unrest in Ukraine begin?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Using this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/12/10/world/europe/ukraine-timeline.html">interactive timeline,</a> you can trace the roots of the current unrest &#8212; from President Viktor F. Yanukovychâs signals in early 2013 that Ukraine would make an agreement with the European Union to the angry protests by the end of the year that flared in Kievâs main square. The timeline offers the option to go deeper by watching embedded videos, viewing slide shows and clicking on articles about related events &#8212; like Ukraineâs<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/11/14/world/europe/ukraine-delays-vote-on-tymoshenkos-release.html"> refusal to free the main opposition leader</a>, Yulia V. Tymoshenko, and the <a href="//thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/12/02/video-of-police-brutality-in-kiev-fuels-rage/">role that YouTube played</a> in rallying opposition protesters.  </p>
<hr/>
<div class="w480"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000002732759" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

