<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why did the unrest escalate in the past two weeks?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Protests in Kiev began in November when it became clear that President Yanukovych had turned his back on an agreement with the European Union. Yet at critical moments since then, the rallies seemed to taper off, as when Russia offered Ukraine a $15 billion lifeline to stem the economic crisis.  Last week the world watched in shock as the protests erupted into violence and the government unraveled. The articles below document when the civic unrest spiraled out of control into chaos.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/21/world/europe/ukraine.html">&#8220;Ukraineâs Forces Escalate Attacks Against Protesters&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/slideshow/2014/02/20/world/europe/21UKRAINE_375.html">&#8220;Renewed Fighting Shatters Truce in Ukraine&#8221;</a> (slide show)</li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/20/world/europe/ukraine.html">&#8220;Ukraine Leader Strains for Grip as Chaos Spreads&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/19/world/europe/ukraine.html">&#8220;Kiev Protesters Set Square Ablaze to Thwart Police&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/17/world/europe/ukrainian-protesters-end-occupation-of-kievs-city-hall.html">&#8220;Protesters Vacate Kievâs City Hall in Deal for Amnesty&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What role do Russia and the West play in the Ukrainian crisis?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The civic unrest in the Ukraine is in many ways an outgrowth of the Cold War, with Russia on the one hand, and the European Union and the United States on the other, jockeying for influence in this former Soviet republic. Read about where President Obama, President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia and the leaders of the European Union stand, and find out how the Ukrainian crisis is deepening the clash between East and West.   </p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/25/world/europe/kremlin-says-ukrainian-instability-threatens-russian-interests.html">&#8220;Kremlin Says Ukrainian Instability Threatens Russian Interests&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/25/world/europe/wary-stance-from-obama.html">&#8220;Wary Stance From Obama on Ukraine&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/24/world/europe/deeply-bound-to-ukraine-putin-watches-and-waits-for-next-move.html">&#8220;Deeply Bound to Ukraine, Putin Watches and Waits for Next Move&#8221;</a></li>
<li>
<a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/21/an-east-west-divide-played-out-on-tv-news/">&#8220;An East-West Divide, Played Out on TV News&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/20/world/europe/violence-in-ukraine-creates-deepening-clash-between-east-and-west.html">&#8220;Violence in Ukraine Creates Deepening Clash Between East and West&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What now?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The president has fled, Parliament has called for new elections, the two sides of Ukraine view the revolution very differently and the country&#8217;s economy is in tatters.  Events are unfolding rapidly, but there are already clues about what might be next for this nation of 45 million people.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/26/world/europe/ukraine.html">&#8220;Infighting Hurts Ukraine Efforts to Form a New Government&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/25/world/europe/ukraine.html">&#8220;Amid Political Upheaval, Ukraine Faces Dire Need for Economic Help&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/25/world/europe/ukraine-parliament.html">&#8220;Ukrainian Protesters See Too Many Familiar Faces in Parliament After Revolution&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/23/world/europe/with-presidents-departure-ukraine-looks-toward-a-murky-future.html">&#8220;With Presidentâs Departure, Ukraine Looks Toward a Murky Future&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong><em>Update: March 3, 2014:</em></strong> <strong>How will the standoff in Crimea be resolved?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As of this past weekend, Russia has deployed a &#8220;phantom army&#8221; across Crimea, the autonomous region of the Ukraine that has an ethnic Russian majority and is home to Russia&#8217;s Black Sea Fleet. Russiaâs foreign minister stated that Russian troops are there to protect ethnic Russians from attacks by Ukrainian ultranationalists.  Meanwhile, the British foreign secretary William Hague on March 3 called Ukraine âthe biggest crisis in Europe in the 21st century.â And President Obama and European leaders are trying to formulate their response to what Mr. Obama declared a âbreach of international law.â</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/04/world/europe/ukraine.html">&#8220;World Leaders Warn Kremlin as Ukraine Standoff Continues&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/03/world/europe/in-crimeas-phantom-war-armed-men-face-unseen-foe.html">&#8220;In Crimeaâs Phantom War, Armed Men Face Unseen Foe&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/04/world/europe/ukraine-united-nations.html">&#8220;At U.N., Russia Points to Ultranationalist Threats in Ukraine&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/03/world/europe/putin-engages-in-test-of-will-over-ukraine.html">&#8220;Putin Engages in Test of Will Over Ukraine&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Going Further |</strong> What do you think will happen in Ukraine? What are the next moves that Russia, the European Union and the United States will make? To get additional insights, you can read the opinions of what some Ukrainian watchers hope will happen:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/26/opinion/has-the-west-already-lost-ukraine.html">&#8220;Has the West Already Lost Ukraine?&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/25/opinion/ukraines-uncertain-future.html">&#8220;Ukraineâs Uncertain Future&#8221;</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/24/opinion/what-the-west-must-do-for-ukraine.html">&#8220;What the West Must Do for Ukraine&#8221;</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make your own predictions, and then monitor the news and see what actually happens.  </p>
<hr/>
<div id="teaching-standards" class="teaching-standards">
	<div class="stndrd-desc">
		<h4>Standards</h4>
		<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This resource may be used to address the academic standards listed below.</p>
		<webonly><a href="#" class="st">View all</a></webonly>
	</div>
	<div class="common-core-standards stndrd hidden">
	<h5><a href="//www.corestandards.org/ELA-Literacy" title="//www.corestandards.org/ELA-Literacy">Common Core E.L.A. Anchor Standards</a></h5>
			<div class="subject">
		<h5>Reading</h5>
		<ul>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>1</strong>&nbsp;<span>Read closely to determine what the text says explicitly and to make logical inferences from it; cite specific textual evidence when writing or speaking to support conclusions drawn from the text.</span></p>
			</li>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>2</strong>&nbsp;<span>Determine central ideas or themes of a text and analyze their development; summarize the key supporting details and ideas.</span></p>
			</li>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>7</strong>&nbsp;<span>Integrate and evaluate content presented in diverse media and formats, including visually and quantitatively, as well as in words.</span></p>
			</li>
					</ul>
	</div>
					<div class="subject">
		<h5>Speaking and Listening</h5>
		<ul>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>1</strong>&nbsp;<span>Prepare for and participate effectively in a range of conversations and collaborations with diverse partners, building on othersâ ideas and expressing their own clearly and persuasively.</span></p>
			</li>
					</ul>
	</div>
</div>
<div class="common-core-standards-mp stndrd hidden">
	<h5><a href="//www.corestandards.org/Math/Practice" title="//www.corestandards.org/Math/Practice">Common Core Standards for Mathematical Practice</a></h5>
	<div class="subject">
		<ul>
					<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>44</strong>&nbsp;<span>Understands the search for community, stability, and peace in an interdependent world.</span></p>
			</li>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>45</strong>&nbsp;<span>Understands major global trends since World War II World History Across the Eras.</span></p>
			</li>
						<li>
				<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>46</strong>&nbsp;<span>Understands long-term changes and recurring patterns in world history.</span></p>
			</li>
					</ul>
	</div>
</div>
</div>
<!-- end .teaching-standards -->
	</div>
		<footer class="entry-footer">
